;\">Cathode rays travel in straight lines and is deflected by electric field. This is obvious because these rays are nothing but electrons. It is also used to produce x &ndash;rays. They consist of tiny particles carrying negative electric charges.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Cathode rays may behave like waves. They exhibit the process of interference and diffraction. This cathode ray will cause gases and fluorescent materials to glow, and will heat metal objects in its path to red heat. Cathode rays travel in straight lines and cast sharp shadows. Unlike light, however, cathode rays are attracted toward a positively charged plate.<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">Example<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">The ray which causes gas molecules to glow is<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A. cathode ray, B. anode ray, C. molecular ray, D. gamma ray<\/span><span style=\"width:14.93pt; display:inline-block;\">&nbsp;<\/span><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">A (2012\/2013, no 6)<\/span><\/strong><\/p>\r\n  <p style=\"margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:10pt; line-height:115%; font-size:11pt;\"><span style=\"font-family:'Times New Roman';\">X-rays arise from energy changes and are due to electrons while &gamma; -rays come from the nucleus<\/span><\/p>\r\n \r\n<\/body>\r\n\r\n<\/html>",
  "chapIndex": "RADIOACTIVITY"
